const faqSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: [
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do appetite suppressant gummies actually work?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Some ingredients in appetite suppressant gummies have clinical evidence for reducing hunger. Glucomannan (konjac root fiber) is the most studied — a meta-analysis of 9 RCTs found it reduced body weight by an average of 0.8kg over 5 weeks when combined with a calorie-controlled diet. It works by expanding in the stomach (absorbing 50x its weight in water) to create a feeling of fullness. Chromium picolinate may reduce food cravings and appetite, particularly for carbohydrates. 5-HTP increases serotonin, which regulates appetite signaling. However, no gummy supplement produces significant weight loss without concurrent dietary changes and calorie reduction.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is glucomannan and how does it suppress appetite?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Glucomannan is a water-soluble dietary fiber derived from the root of the konjac plant (Amorphophallus konjac). It is one of the most viscous dietary fibers known — it can absorb up to 50 times its weight in water. When consumed before meals with adequate water, glucomannan expands in the stomach, creating physical distension that triggers stretch receptors and satiety signals to the brain. This reduces the volume of food consumed at the subsequent meal. The EU has approved a health claim that glucomannan contributes to weight loss when consumed at 3g per day in the context of a calorie-restricted diet.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'When should I take appetite suppressant gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Take appetite suppressant gummies 30-60 minutes before meals with at least 8oz (240ml) of water. The timing allows fiber-based ingredients (glucomannan) to expand in the stomach before food arrives, maximizing the satiety effect. Water is essential — glucomannan requires water to expand and create the fullness sensation. Without adequate water, glucomannan can cause throat or esophageal blockage. For best results, take before the 1-2 meals where you tend to overeat the most. Some people find taking before dinner most effective, as evening overeating is the most common pattern.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Are appetite suppressant gummies safe?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Fiber-based appetite suppressants (glucomannan, inulin) are generally safe when taken with adequate water. The main risk is esophageal or intestinal blockage if taken without sufficient water — always consume with at least 8oz of water. Digestive side effects (bloating, gas, cramps) are common when starting fiber supplementation, especially in people with low baseline fiber intake. Start with half the recommended dose and increase gradually. 5-HTP should not be combined with antidepressants (SSRIs, MAOIs) due to serotonin syndrome risk. Chromium is safe at recommended doses but can interact with diabetes medications. Pregnant and breastfeeding women should avoid appetite suppressants.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much weight can I lose with appetite suppressant gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Clinical studies on glucomannan show an average weight loss of 0.8kg (approximately 1.8 lbs) over 5 weeks compared to placebo, when combined with a calorie-controlled diet. This is modest but statistically significant. The real value of appetite suppressants is making calorie restriction more sustainable — reducing the hunger and cravings that cause most diets to fail. By making you feel fuller with less food, they support adherence to a calorie deficit over weeks and months. A 500-calorie daily deficit produces approximately 1 pound of fat loss per week. Appetite suppressant gummies help maintain that deficit, but they do not replace it.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I take appetite suppressant gummies with other supplements?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Fiber-based appetite suppressants can reduce the absorption of medications and other supplements taken at the same time. Take medications and critical supplements at least 1-2 hours before or after fiber-based gummies. Do not combine 5-HTP appetite suppressants with antidepressants (serotonin syndrome risk). Chromium can interact with diabetes medications (hypoglycemia risk). Appetite suppressant gummies can be safely combined with most vitamins, probiotics, and protein when timing is separated appropriately. Always consult your healthcare provider about specific medication interactions.' } },
