      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="brain" size={22} /></div><strong>5-HTP — Serotonin Satiety</strong><p>5-Hydroxytryptophan is a serotonin precursor that increases the brain's satiety signaling. A 1998 study found 5-HTP supplementation reduced caloric intake by 38% and increased satiety in overweight women. Do NOT combine with antidepressants.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="scale" size={22} /></div><strong>Chromium — Craving Reduction</strong><p>Chromium picolinate enhances insulin receptor sensitivity, potentially reducing carbohydrate and sugar cravings. A meta-analysis found modest reductions in body weight (-0.5kg) and food intake with chromium supplementation.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div><strong>Fiber — Slow Digestion</strong><p>Soluble fiber (inulin, pectin, psyllium) slows gastric emptying, prolonging the feeling of fullness after meals. Fiber also feeds beneficial gut bacteria, which produce short-chain fatty acids that signal satiety to the brain via the gut-brain axis.</p></div>
    </div>

